## Notes Section (Technical Commentary & References)

### Prologue and Chapter 1 Notes

**Bell curve**: Gaussian bell curve (normal distribution). Visual histogram masks contribution of remote events (far right/left of center).

**Diamonds**: See Eco (2002).

**Platonicity**: Risk of using wrong form — not that forms don't exist. Skeptical of reverse engineering and identification of right form (inverse problem).

**Empiricist**: Suspicious of confirmatory generalizations and hasty theorizing. Do not confuse with British empiricist tradition. Many statisticians call themselves "empirical" but are opposite — they fit theories to past.

**Mention of Christ**: See **Flavius Josephus**'s *The Jewish War*.

**Great War and prediction**: Ferguson (2006b).

**Hindsight bias (retrospective distortion)**: See Fischhoff (1982b).

**Historical fractures**: **Braudel** (1985) quotes **Émile-Félix Gautier**: "This long history lasted a dozen centuries, longer than entire history of France. Encountering first Arab sword, Greek language and thought, all that heritage went up in smoke, as if it never happened." See also Gurvitch (1957), Braudel (1953), Harris (2004).

**Religions spread as bestsellers**: Veyne (1971, 2005).

**Clustering in political opinions**: Pinker (2002).

**Categories**: Rosch (1973, 1978). See also Umberto Eco's *Kant and the Platypus*.

**Historiography and philosophy of history**: Bloch (1953), Carr (1961), Gaddis (2002), Braudel (1969, 1990), Bourlé and Martin (1989), Certeau (1975). *Muqaddimah* by **Ibn Khaldoun** illustrates search for causation already present in **Herodotus**. For philosophy of history: Aron (1961), Fukuyama (1992). For postmodern views: Jenkins (1991). Historiographers unaware of epistemological difference between forward and backward processes (projection vs. reverse engineering).

**Information and markets**: See Shiller (1981, 1989), DeLong et al. (1991), Cutler et al. (1989). Bulk of market moves does not have "reason" — just contrived explanation.

**Of descriptive value for crashes**: See Galbraith (1997), Shiller (2000), Kindleberger (2001).

### Chapter 3 Notes

**Movies**: See De Vany (2002). See also Salganik et al. (2006) for contagion in music buying.

**Religion and domains of contagion**: See Boyer (2001).

**Wisdom (madness) of crowds**: Collectively can get wiser or far more foolish. May have intuitions for Mediocristan-related matters (weight of ox — see Surowiecki, 2004), but fail in complicated predictions (economic variables requiring nonlinear incur pathologies — two heads worse than one). For decision errors and groups: Sniezek and Buckley (1993). Classic: **Charles Mackay**'s *Extraordinary Popular Delusions and the Madness of Crowds*.

**Increase in severity of events**: Zajdenweber (2000).

**Modern life**: **Émile Zola** welcomed market for culture arrival (late 1800s) — predicted writers'/artists' ability to exploit commercial system freed them from patrons' whims. Accompanied with more severe concentration — very few benefited. Lahire (2006) shows most writers throughout history have starved. Ample data from France about literary tradition.

### Chapter 4 Notes

**Titanic**: Quote from **Dave Ingram**'s presentation at Enterprise Risk Management Symposium (Chicago, May 2, 2005). For LTCM: Lowenstein (2000), Dunbar (1999).

**Hume's exposition**: Hume (1748, 2000).

**Sextus Empriricius**: "Easy to reject method of induction." Cannot make universals convincing from particulars — surveying all particulars or some will lead to infirm induction. *Outline of Pyrrhonism*, Book II, p. 204.

**Bayle**: *Dictionnaire historique et critique* (twelve volumes, 6,000 pages, 40 pounds) — intellectual bestseller, being supplanted by *philosophes*. Can be downloaded from French Bibliothèque Nationale at www.bn.fr.

**Hume's inspiration from Bayle**: See Popkin (1951, 1955). Any reading of **Bishop Huet** would reveal similarities with Hume.

**Pre-Bayle thinkers**: *Dissertation sur la recherche de la vérité* by **Simon Foucher** (~1673) — delight to read. Makes heuristics and biases tradition look like continuation of pre-Enlightenment prescientific revolution atmosphere.

**Bishop Huet and problem of induction**: "Things cannot be known with perfect certainty because their causes are infinite" — **Pierre-Daniel Huet** in *Philosophical Treatise on the Weaknesses of the Human Mind*. Former bishop of Avranches, wrote under name **Théocrite de Pluvinel**, **Seigneur de la Roche**, **Gentilhomme de Périgord**. Contains exact presentation of what became "Hume's problem" (1690, when future David Home was minus twenty-two — no possible influence on Monseigneur Huet).

**Brochard's work**: First encountered in **Nietzsche**'s *Ecce Homo* describing skeptics as straight talkers. "Excellent study by **Victor Brochard**, *Les sceptiques grecs*, in which my Laertiana also employed." Skeptics only *honourable* type among ambiguous philosopher crowd. **More trivit**: Brochard taught **Proust** (see Kristeva, 1998).

- Brochard understood **Popper**'s problem (decades before Popper's birth)
- Presents views of negative empiricism of **Menodotus of Nicomedia** in similar terms to "Popperian" empiricism
- Wonder if Popper knew about Menodotus (does not quote him anywhere)
- Brochard published doctoral thesis *De l'erreur* (1878) at University of Paris — wonderfully modern subject

**Epilogism**: Know very little about **Menodotus** except attacks by detractor **Galen** in Latin *Outline of Empiricism* (*Subfiguratio empirica*), hard to translate.

- According to **Perilli** (2004), letter by translator **Is-haq Bin Hunain** reports may be "transcription" of Menodotus's work in Arabic somewhere for scholar to find

**Pascal**: Had idea of confirmation problem and asymmetry of inference. In preface to *Traité du vide*: "In judgment they made that nature did not tolerate vacuum, they only meant nature in state they knew it — would not be sufficient to witness in hundred different encounters or thousand — would be single case denying general definition if one was contrary."

**Hume's biographer**: Mossner (1970). For history of skepticism: **Victor Cousin**'s lectures *Leçons d'histoire de la philosophie à la Sorbonne* (1828) and **Hippolyte Taine**'s *Les philosophes classiques* (9th edition, 1868, 1905). Popkin (2003) modern account. See also Heckman (2003) and Bevan (1913) — seen nothing in modern philosophy of probability linking to skeptical inquiry.

**Sextus**: See Popkin (2003), Sextus, House (1980), Bayle, Huet, Annas and Barnes (1985), Julia Anna and Barnes's introduction in Sextus Empiricus (2000). Favier (1906) hard to find — only copy located (thanks to **Gur Huberman**) was rotten, not consulted in past hundred years.

**Menodotus of Nicomedia and marriage between empiricism and skepticism**: According to Brochard (1887), **Menodotus** responsible for mixing empiricism and Pyrrhonism. See also Favier (1906). See skepticism about this in Dye (2004) and Perilli (2004).

**Function not structure; empirical tripod**: Three sources only for experience: observation, history (recorded observation), judgment by analogy.

**Algazel**: See his *Tahafut al falasifah*, rebutted by **Averroës** (Ibn-Rushd) in *Tahafut Attahafut*.

**Religious skeptics**: Also medieval Jewish tradition with Arabic-speaking poet **Yehuda Halevi**. See Floridi (2002).

**Algazel and ultimate/proximate causation**: "...their determining, from sole observation, of nature of necessary relationship between cause and effect, as if one could not witness effect without attributed cause of cause without same effect." (*Tahafut*)

- Core of Algazel's idea: if drink because thirsty, thirst should not be seen as *direct* cause
- May be greater scheme played out — can only be understood by those familiar with evolutionary thinking
- See Tinbergen (1963, 1968) for modern account of proximate
- In way, Algazel builds on **Aristotle** to attack him
- In *Physics*, Aristotle already seen distinction between different layers of cause (formal, efficient, final, material)

**Modern discussions on causality**: See Reichenbach (1938), Granger (1999), Pearl (2000).

**Children and natural induction**: See Gelman and Coley (1990), Gelman and Hirschfeld (1999), Sloman (1993).

**Natural induction**: See Hespos (2006), Clark and Boyer (2006), Inagaki and Hatano (2006), Reboul (2006). See summary of earlier works in Plotkin (1998).
