- **Carter et al.** (1962), **Shackle** (1961, 1973), **Hayek** (1994), **Hirshleifer and Riley** (1992) fits uncertainty into neoclassical economics

### Incommutability

- For earthquakes: **Freedman and Stark** (2003) (courtesy **Gur Huberman**)

### Academia and Philistinism

- Round-trip fallacy: academia means rigor (doubtful), but "**peer reviewing**" often masquerade
- Nonacademic doesn't imply nonrigorous
- By **confirmation bias**, academics show contributions despite high number laboring
- Minute fraction of results come from academics
- Disproportionately high contributions from freelance researchers and "amateurs": **Darwin**, **Freud**, **Marx**, **Mandelbrot**, even early **Einstein**
- Influence by academic usually accidental
- Held in Middle Ages and Renaissance — see **Le Goff** (1985)
- Enlightenment figures (**Voltaire**, **Rousseau**, **d'Holbach**, **Diderot**, **Montesquieu**) all nonacademics when academia was large

## Chapter 10

### Overconfidence

- **Albert and Raiffa** (1982) — paper languished decade before formal publication
- **Lichtenstein and Fischhoff** (1977): overconfidence influenced by item difficulty; turns into underconfidence in easy items
- Compare with **Armelius** [1979]
- Many papers tried pinning down conditions of calibration failures/robustness: task training, ecological aspects, education level, nationality
- Studies: **Dawes** (1980), **Koriat, Lichtenstein, and Fischhoff** (1980), **Mayseless and Kruglanski** (1987), **Dunning et al.** (1990), **Ayton and McClelland** (1997), **Ferrell and Odean** (1999), **Griffin and Varey** (1996), **Juslin** (1991, 1993, 1994), **Juslin and Olsson** (1997), **Kadane and Lichtenstein** (1982), **May** (1986), **McClelland and Bolger** (1994), **Pfeifer** (1994), **Russo and Schoernaker** (1992), **Klayman et al.** (1999)
- Unexpected decrease in overconfidence under group decisions: **Sniezek and Henry** (1989)
- Solutions in **Plous** (1995)
- Suspicious of **Mediocristan/Extremistan** distinction and unevenness of variables
- Found no paper making this distinction
- Solutions in **Stoll** (1996), **Arkes et al.** (1987)
- Finance: **Thorley** (1999), **Barber and Odean** (1999)
- Cross-boundaries effects: **Yates et al.** (1996, 1998), **Angele et al.** (1982)
- Simultaneous overconfidence and underconfidence: **Erev, Wallsten, and Budescu** (1994)

### Frequency vs. Probability—The Ecological Problem

- **Hoffrage and Gigerenzer** (1998): overconfidence less significant when problem expressed in **frequencies** vs. probabilities
- Debate between "ecology" and laboratory
- See **Gigerenzer et al.** (2000), **Gigerenzer and Richter** (1990), **Gigerenzer** (1991)
- "Fast and frugal" (**Gigerenzer and Goldstein** [1996])
- As far as Black Swan concerned, ecology problems don't arise: we don't live in environment with supplied frequencies or for which we are fit
- In ecology: **Spariosu** (2004) for ludic aspect, **Cosmides and Tooby** (1990)
- **Leary** (1987) for Brunswikian ideas, **Brunswik** (1952)

### Lack of Awareness of Ignorance

> "In short, the same knowledge that underlies the ability to produce correct judgment is also the knowledge that underlies the ability to recognize correct judgment. To lack the former is to be deficient in the latter." — **Kruger and Dunning** (1999)

### Expert Problem in Isolation

- Sees expert problem as indistinguishable from **Matthew effects** and **Extremism fat tails**
- Found no such link in sociology/psychology literatures

### Clinical Knowledge and Its Problems

- **Meehl** (1954), **Dawes, Faust, and Meehl** (1989)
- Most entertaining: essay "**Why I Do Not Attend Case Conferences**" in **Meehl** (1973)
- See also **Wagenaar and Keren** (1985, 1986)

### Financial Analysts, Herding, and Forecasting

- **Guedj and Bouchaud** (2006), **Abarbanell and Bernard** (1992), **Chen et al.** (2002), **De Bondt and Thaler** (1990), **Easterwood and Nutt** (1999), **Friesen and Weller** (2002), **Foster** (1977), **Hong and Kubik** (2003), **Jacob et al.** (1999), **Lim** (2001), **Liu** (1998), **Maines and Hand** (1996), **Mendenhall** (1991), **Mikhail et al.** (1997, 1999), **Zitzewitz** (2001), **El-Galfy and Forbes** (2005)
- Comparison with weather forecasters (unfavorable): **Tyszka and Zielonka** (2002)

### Economists and Forecasting

- **Tetlock** (2005), **Makridakis and Hibon** (2000), **Makridakis et al.** (1982, 1993), **Gripaios** (1994), **Armstrong** (1978, 1981)
- Rebuttals by **McNees** (1978), **Tashman** (2000), **Blake** (1986), **Onkal et al.** (2003), **Gillespie** (1979), **Baron** (2004), **Batchelor** (1990, 2001), **Dominitz and Grether** (1999)
- **Lamont** (2002): established forecasters get worse as they produce more radical forecasts to get attention—consistent with **Tetlock's hedgehog effect**
- **Ahiya and Doi** (2001) look for herd behavior in Japan
- See **McNees** (1995), **Remus et al.** (1997), **O'Neill and Desar** (2005), **Bewley and Fiebig** (2002), **Angner** (2006), **Bénassy-Quéré** (2002), **Brender and Pisani** (2001) look at Bloomberg consensus
- **De Bondt and Kappler** (2004) claim evidence of weak persistence in 52 years of data, but Taleb saw slides in presentation, never the paper, which might never materialize after two years
- **Overconfidence**: **Braun and Yaniv** (1992)
- See **Hahn** (1993) for general intellectual discussion
- More general: **Clemen** (1986, 1989)
- Game theory: **Green** (2005)

### Popular Culture and Forecasting

- Many operators (**James Montier**) and magazines (*The Economist*) run casual tests
- Cumulatively must be taken seriously since they cover more variables

### Popular Culture Examples

- 1931: **Edward Angly** exposed forecasts made by President Hoover in book titled *Oh Yeah?*
- Hilarious book: **Cerf and Navasky** (1998) where Taleb incidentally got pre-1973 oil-estimation story

### Effects of Information

- Major paper: **Bruner and Potter** (1964)
- Thanks to **Danny Kahneman** for pointing out this paper
- See also **Montier** (2007), **Oskamp** (1965), **Benartzi** (2001)
- Biases become ambiguous information (**Griffin and Tversky** [1992])
- How they fail to disappear with expertise/training: **Kahneman and Tversky** (1982), **Tversky and Kahneman** (1982)
- **Kunda** (1990): preference-consistent information taken at face value, preference-inconsistent information processed critically

### Planning Fallacy

- **Kahneman and Tversky** (1979), **Buehler, Griffin, and Ross** (2002)
- Shows consistent bias in people's planning ability even with repeatable matters
- More exaggerated with nonrepeatable events

### Other Topics (Chapter 10)

- **Wars**: **Trivers** (2002)
- **Delay incentives**: **Flyvbjerg et al.** (2002)
- **Oskamp**: **Oskamp** (1965), **Montier** (2007)
- **Task characteristics**: **Shanteau** (1992)
- **Epistêmê vs. Technê**: Distinction harks back to Aristotle, recurs in accounts of tacit knowledge in "know how" — see **Ryle** (1949), **Polanyi** (1958/1974), **Mokyr** (2002)
- **Catherine the Great**: Number of lovers from **Rounding** (2006)
- **Life expectancy**: www.annuityadvantage.com/lifeexpectancy.htm — uses probability of exceeding with power-law exponent 3/2: f= Kx^(3/2), giving conditional expectation formula

