### Philosophy of Intellectual Engagement

> "It is unfortunate that one learns most from people one disagrees with—something Montaigne encouraged half a millennium ago but is rarely practiced."

- Disagreement puts arguments through robust seasoning
- Detractors identify slightest cracks, reveal limits of theories and weaknesses in your own
- Learned tricks from debates with: **Robert C. Merton, Steve Ross, Myron Scholes, Philippe Jorion** (dozens of others)
  - Last heard something remotely new against ideas in 1994 (except Elie Ayache's critique)
- Debates valuable for understanding extent of counterarguments and how detractors think

### Reading Strategy

- Reads more material from those he disagrees with than those he agrees with:
  - More **Samuelson** than **Hayek**
  - More **Merton** (younger) than **Merton** (elder)
  - More **Hegel** than **Montaigne**
  - More **Descartes** than **Sextus**
- Duty to represent adversaries' ideas as faithfully as possible

### Personal Relationships

> "My greatest accomplishment in life is to have managed to befriend people, such as Elie Ayache and Jim Gatheral, in spite of some intellectual disagreements."

### Writing Environment

- Peripatetic period: freed from business obligations, routines, pressures
- Urban walks in various cities, gave lecture series on Black Swan idea
- Wrote largely in cafés—preference for dilapidated but elegant cafés in regular neighborhoods
- Avoided strained businessmen (allergy to their presence)
- **Heathrow Terminal 4**: absorbed in writing, forgot about allergy

### Personal Anecdotes (Footnotes)

- Lost business card but warmly thanked scientist traveling to Vienna aboard British Airways flight 700 (November 2003) for suggesting "Umberto Eco's antilibrary" concept
  - Description: fifty-two, gray-haired, English-born, wrote poetry on yellow notepads, traveling with seven suitcases and thirty-five-year-old Viennese girlfriend
- **On deep work**: impossible to go deep into an idea when running a business
  - Worries and responsibility feelings occupy cognitive space
  - Can study, meditate, write as employee but not as business owner (unless irresponsible)
  - Thanks partner **Mark Spitznagel** for enabling systematic, disciplined approach to gain rare event exposure without direct business involvement

### Author Bio Section

- **Nassim Nicholas Taleb**: devoted life to problems of luck, uncertainty, probability, knowledge
- Three careers: man of letters, businessman-trader, university professor
- Spends most time as flâneur meditating in cafés across the planet
- **Distinguished Professor** at New York University's Polytechnic Institute
- **Principal** of Universa LP
- Books *Fooled by Randomness* and *The Black Swan* published in thirty-one languages

